Republican strategy to resist reelection of Obama
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat election fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, claiming that election fraud is less common in the United States than death by lightning.
And Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of election fraud in the United States in the last decade.
One thing is for sure: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In that sense, this kind of action is partly discrediting the American democratic system.
Unlike Canada, the states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That's why most state governments have passed laws since 2009 that make it harder to register or vote.
This phenomenon gained new momentum after the November 2010 election, which brought Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, in 2011 alone, 180 bills restricting voting rights were passed in 41 states.
New election laws require voters to show photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws shorten the period of early voting, abolish the right to register on the day of the vote and deprive citizens with criminal records of the right to vote.
Before the 2006 election, no U.S. state required voters to present photo IDs.
Indiana was the first state to make such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of a law passed in Indiana in 2008.
Republican officials quickly expanded the practice to other states.
Over the past two years, they've introduced bills requiring voters to show photo IDs in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have a universal identity card such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11 percent of American citizens, or 21 million people over the voting age, do not have a photo ID issued by their state's government agency.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
The cost of obtaining the required ID card is often over $100.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25 percent of African Americans, 15 percent of people earning less than $35,000, 18 percent of citizens over age 65, and 20 percent of voters between 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Student voters who are believed to be voting for Democratic candidates are banned in several states from using photo IDs issued by their school.
But these same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, which vote mostly for Republicans, to use ballot papers issued by those clubs.
Until 2004, no state required proof of U.S. citizenship to vote.
This requirement was first introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are obviously aimed at limiting the voting of Latin Americans.
It is estimated that two-thirds of Latin American voters vote for the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated legislation in 2011 to abolish voter registration on Election Day in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to assist those who wish to register.
This restriction did not go unchecked.
For example, during the 2004 election, a campaign to register voters helped to register some 10 million people.
At the same time, measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17% drop in the level of new voter registration in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican lawmakers passed laws in five other states aimed at shortening the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 general election in Florida, 33% of early voters were African-American, although the latter made up only 13% of the state's total voters.
The same thing happened with the Latin Americans.
While they represented only 11% of the electorate, they made up 24% of the citizens who voted early.
Unlike whites, who make up 76 percent of the electorate, only 46 percent of early voters cast ballots.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters are actively opposed to passing laws that restrict voter registration.
Several bills have been vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most controversial laws were suspended by the United States Attorney General.
This partially reduced the negative effects.
For example, only 16 of the 34 states have passed laws requiring photo ID.
However, the new rules that have come into force will certainly make it harder to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Critics of the legislation, who see it as clearly intended to influence the outcome of the 2012 election in key states, have condemned the bias of the legislation.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 electoral votes needed to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new regulations will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In that sense, this kind of action is partly discrediting the American democratic system.
