The Higgs boson in detail
Last summer, the news that scientists may have discovered the Higgs boson caused quite a stir - and for good reason.
This boson is thought to explain the mass of all the particles in the universe, no less.
It's also the last particle predicted by the Standard Model -- our best, or at least least least least imperfect, description of the nature and behavior of matter -- but never before detected experimentally.
But physicists are not sure that this is the Higgs boson.
We know without a shadow of a doubt that we're dealing with a really new particle and that it strongly resembles the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
Also, new data presented this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seems to support this, although some data are not yet available for full certainty.
But let's say we're talking about the Higgs boson, because the chances of getting it wrong seem minimal, and let's see what that means.
There is one law in this world that is completely unavoidable, which is that no two things can be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way around this rule, even if you try too hard, or you will hurt yourself.
But while particle physics is a rather strange world, it turns out that it also has a law of this nature: the Pauli exclusion principle, which postulates that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same moment in time if they are in the same quantum state -- that state is, in general, some of their characteristics.
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find good citizens called fermions who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
The other is a bunch of bosons, a nasty bunch of anarchists who have no respect for anything -- at least this principle, which means they can be in the same place at the same time.
According to the (by the way, quite unusual) Particle Adventure website of Berkeley Laboratories, these bosons are divided into two groups: mesons, which we won't talk about here, and "force particles", which are the primary forces of nature and to which the Higgs boson belongs in some way.
These bosons themselves, it should be emphasized, are not all as exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you can read this chronicle, it's because of one incredibly common boson: the photon, or "particle of light", which is the "courier" of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a single particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it "disrupts" the electromagnetic field in that particular location, much like a rock thrown into a pond.
From this "violation" arises an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.), and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons of the "force carriers".
More stable field
The same thing happens with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that in order for this boson to appear, another field, the Higgs field, has to be broken.
But the Higgs field is much, much more stable than an electromagnetic field; it needs to reach very, very high energies to be excited, like a frozen pond, the surface of which can only be shaken by a very large rock.
That's why you need a huge particle accelerator like the one that's running at CERN -- the Large Hadron Collider, which is a 17-mile-diameter ring! -- to achieve these enormous energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with an electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, interact, while others do not: a sheet of paper, for example, will never hold on a refrigerator by itself.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that interact have mass, while others (like the photon, by the way) do not.
So what "can" all this research bring, asks Plamondon?
In science, they are used to test the accuracy of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to feel the discrepancy between the results of observations and the predictions of the SM.
And some of them are desperate to see that discrepancy revealed, because the slightest discrepancy could open the door to a new physics and plug some of the Model holes.
The latter, I must say, still has significant flaws, offering no explanation for gravity (wow!) or for dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the universe (wow!).
But so far, CERN has not found any such discrepancies.
The Consequences
The benefits of these studies for the average person's daily life are harder to predict, but it would be a mistake to assume that they don't.
Look, in the early '60s, the pioneers of laser research at Bell Labs couldn't have even imagined the revolution their work would cause.
They saw their applications in science, but nothing more.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (the previous ones were pulsed) in 1962, said that initially the laser was considered more like a "laboratory gadget".
Can you imagine?
And then there's the application for the tools that go with the research.
For example, the same Willard Boyle, during his optical research in 1969, developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, though not at all its original purpose, now serves as the eye for all the world's digital cameras and won the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
This doesn't mean, of course, that the work of the Large Hadron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it just shows, in fact, that anything can be.
Palliative care is the best way to die...
The Quebec Commission for the Decency of Death recently discussed the delicate issue of the end of life.
The debate is due to resume soon, and a bill is being drafted.
However, much remains to be done in this vital area.
"Due" tried to take a closer look.
Only a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was still living alone in his apartment in Monteregio.
Prostate cancer, which was destroying him from the inside, gave him a two-year reprieve.
"I was given five years, I lived seven", he says, between life and death, lying in bed at the Victor-Hadboua hospice in Belley, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, and you can't prepare for it", he says.
The disease does its job: an incredible weakness that prevents you from going to the toilet or even eating on your own.
Sitting at a table with a tasty meal, he gives in and accepts help to assimilate his food.
He's cheerful, even able to smile, to talk to strangers who work around him, bring him medicine, take him to the bathroom.
Courage in the face of a normal death.
"My greatest desire is to be cured of diarrhea", he admits.
A few hours later, the staff found a cure for the disease.
"We are taught all our lives that a man should urinate standing up", says Pierre Broder, a psychologist at the Victor-Hadboua shelter.
To regress to the condition of a child is an unbearable humiliation for some.
"It all depends on the person's ability" to cope with decline, he says.
Because, according to many palliative care practitioners, major events happen at the height of this decline.
The patients who come to Victor Hadboe's hospice are all cancer patients.
The prognosis is three months to life at most.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses no longer provide the care called "medication".
Mrs. A., 89, has a fear of dying "conscious of suffocation".
But the illness allowed me to get to know my children.
"I have good children", she adds.
"I don't want anything else in life", she says before being allowed to wear a mask to help her breathe.
She is still waiting for the last visit of her son, who came from Italy.
The Victor-Hadboua shelter provides care and nutrition with the help of a group of volunteers.
This is palliative care, which is left over when there's nothing else to do.
To make death more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one place in a palliative care facility for every 11,700 people.
That's not much considering we all die sooner or later.
Life here continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christian Martel, one of the doctors at the shelter.
Whether it's physical, emotional, or spiritual comfort.
We'll give a dying man a mouthwash of brandy or Pepsi, whatever he asks for.
We don't make diabetics control their blood sugar anymore.
And death is part of the everyday.
Last night we brought beer to Mr. H, who died tonight.
His son finished this beer at the dead man's feet this morning.
"We help the family as well as the patients", says Natalie Savar, director of patient care.
At the Victor-Hadbou shelter, no day is the same as the last.
Next to a 93-year-old man enjoying his last meeting with his family in the yard, reclining on his pillows during a toast in his honor, a 36-year-old man dies tragically, surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children and having tried everything to survive.
"In the last six months, three to five beds have been occupied by cancer patients under 45", worries Dr. Christian Martel.
53% of patients admitted to the Victor-Hadbou shelter come from home, and 47% from the hospital.
Access to palliative care
It is estimated that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, which is care provided to alleviate the suffering of patients entering their final stages of life, whether at home, in a hospital, or in a nursing home.
And some institutions, like the Victor Hadbou Shelter and the Palliative Care Home Society of Greater Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in cancer care.
It is this gap in Quebec's health care system that has many palliative care doctors worried about legislation legalizing euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been circulating from the world's leading palliative care practitioners, Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lapaunt, expressing their disapproval of the initiative.
According to Dr. Christian Martel, Quebec's health care system is not efficient enough to provide the right to high-quality palliative care before euthanasia is allowed.
She says, "I recently saw a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency room in excruciating pain, and no one took the necessary steps to relieve her.
I'm afraid the only reason patients want to die is because they're not getting adequate care.
At the same time, many oncologists are working to the end to save their patients despite pessimistic forecasts.
Helen Richard's chances of survival were already minimal when she stopped the grueling chemo.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping my treatment, she said that she regretted stopping the fight", she says.
She told me that my days were numbered!
There is no cure
Dr. Martel believes that 90 percent of patients who ask to die thank the health care staff for not granting their request after the palliative care team relieves their pain.
However, palliative care is not an all-powerful pain reliever.
According to Elsie Monroe, director of palliative care at the Greater Montreal Home Palliative Care Society, patients are not responsive to pain medication in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, where the patient is put to sleep until the moment of death, either intermittently or permanently.
We can no longer pretend that we don't know about this suffering.
More and more patients who cannot relieve pain will be able to access palliative sedation.
Patients who suffer from pain always say the same phrase: "I want to die".
But that doesn't necessarily mean "I want to be euthanized", it means "I want to feel better".
