Pay and sell without banks - with Bitcoin
The complete opposite of current money exchange, based on central banks, numbered transactions between receiving parties with processing fees.
And as is often the case with these technologies, there is a political vision that is obvious: the belief that the current monetary system, which consists of banking monopolies, is leading to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible into dollars, euros...) and a secure BitTorrent-type exchange protocol that allows file sharing between participants of the same level.
About 200,000 transactions have already been registered from 15,000 computers on the network.
Several thousand sites accept Bitcoin for donations or as a form of payment.
The bitcoin price peaked at $30 (€23) in June 2011, dropped to $2 five months later, before returning to around $10 today (rates are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the global exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on virtual currency published in October showed interest in the system.
He describes Bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies as "credits" used to promote a video game, which are earned during the game or which can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But the exchange is always controlled and processed by some central authority.
In Bitcoin, all nodes are simultaneously accountants, auditors, issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users actually happens between two email addresses, just like an email.
Only for each new payment can the user choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The information set relating to this transaction is signed electronically, using a double-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
The contents of the file allow us to verify that the bitcoins used in the transaction actually exist in a public ledger that is being sent out across the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this ledger.
It goes through solving a mathematical problem, sent to the computers, and the solver, like a temporary central bank, gets the privilege of adding this new line.
It's the hashing phase of a file, which is the conversion of a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
The computers take the new transaction and add a number to it before hashing it all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, other nodes can easily check that it's correct.
The transaction is thus inextricably linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
