The chief of the inspection department says the blacklisting failed because of politicians.
The Czech Republic has good control authorities in the public procurement sector and, despite having quality legislation, is lagging behind in its application.
This is Miroslav Kal, vice president of the Supreme Audit Office, from an interview with Aktuálně.cz.
"The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly, which I think we lack", commented Kala on the current situation.
The Czech and German inspection authorities have issued similar reports.
An example of a wrong practice is the approach of Peter Nechas to the so-called Schwarz-System.
The Prime Minister recently said that the GDP (Civil Democratic Party) will not bother entrepreneurs with inspections - is this prohibited or allowed?
"The law should be established in some way, and if it prohibits something, then the prime minister cannot stand in the way of the institutions that are charged with checking and enforcing the obligations", says Kala.
At the House of Representatives' audit committee, you spoke about a joint project between the Czech and German parties to compare the public procurement legislation of both countries.
What was the point?
I mean, a parallel check we started, like, two years ago.
In other words, European legislation sets out how public procurement should be conducted, followed by national legislation and then also practical application.
All the information has been collected and, even with the unfinished investigation, interesting differences have been found - in simple terms, we may have a "precise and error-free" legislation, but in practice we are behind Germany in some parameters.
This means that it is not enough to create more and more detailed rules, we need to focus on the application of the law itself.
And how exactly can this project help you, what does it mean to you?
It is this kind of joint control that can help stop the effort to clarify laws, reduce and improve restrictions, because it does not lead to a positive result.
Economics means getting the right thing for a reasonable (but not always low) price to avoid enrichment and possibly criminal behavior.
But it's not the fact that we're going to get there by reducing the order limit.
Perhaps the system will become so overwhelmed with paperwork that those who wish to find loopholes in the system will find them much easier than if the restriction had not been relaxed.
You're talking about the internal problems of the practical application of public procurement legislation.
How does the control system work in Germany?
Is there an organization like our C.R.U. or does it work differently?
As for the institutions, there is the Bundesrechnungshof, which is our CRU, and it is organized in our way. There is also a board that works a little differently, but basically both institutions work in the same way.
In addition, the powers are similar to a certain extent, but since Germany has a federal structure, there are audit units at the level of the federal states - in this their system is somewhat different from ours.
BRH can only manage federal money, we have public funds.
Public funds in our regions and municipalities are controlled at the level of the Federal Accounts Chamber.
As far as local laws go, is it easier there than here?
I don't want to make a comparison without specific data, but in some ways Germany is a good example, but you can't say for sure that it's better in everything.
Is it because they're better at controlling?
Definitely not, but I don't like comparisons like that.
But even the best countries face many challenges.
Otherwise, they wouldn't have any advantage from working with our office, would they?
Speaking of domestic legislation, how did the amendments to the Public Procurement Act affect your institution, are there any consequences?
Given that the legal force of these amendments is quite short, it has not yet been demonstrated in our control work.
Since we're conducting a fact-finding mission, we're going to have to take into account some delays.
We're just taking this into account in the process of preparing future audits -- we've started using our new tool called the "discount risk detection" tool, which we've run through almost 14,000 government contracts. We've analyzed them.
Do you think that passing this law will bring benefits or additional burden on the bureaucratic system?
I think this law is definitely a step in the right direction, and I hope it proves it.
The problem that can arise is that the rules become so harsh that they become unenforceable.
Under the previous rules, controlled enterprises are linked to the supplier (e.g. regional operational programmes - to the regional council) in that any non-compliance with the public procurement law means a breach of budgetary discipline.
Should the law be tightened in this way?
I don't think it's that way.
The system should exclude those who want to seize and abuse, but not punish those who make a formal mistake that doesn't affect the decision.
Such a system would only create even more pressure on the bureaucracy.
So how do you get out of this situation?
Let's face it, this road leads nowhere.
The Prime Minister recently said that the GOP would not bother businessmen with the so-called Schwarz system.
Is the Schwartz system prohibited or allowed?
The law should be in place in some way, and if it prohibits something, the prime minister cannot stand in the way of the bodies charged with checking and enforcing the obligations.
You can say, "We're going to change this law and we're going to allow this", but you can't say we're going to pretend like nothing's happening.
The Public Procurement Act has pretty strict rules about how and what should be done formally, and that's right.
But on the other hand, it's tragic when the candidate with the best offer is disqualified solely because of formal flaws.
The law will never be perfect, but it must be applied correctly, which I think we lack.
