We want to build up positive energy at concerts .
What do you think about the world ending in less than a month?
This is just one of the many disturbing news stories that we humans are so easily exposed to.
And with The Tap Tap, we joke about it all the time, saying that we're the only band in the world that can muster enough positive energy to delay or prevent the end of the world.
In addition, in December you are going to give three absolutely unique concerts against the end of the world.
Could you tell us more about that?
This is a nationwide fundraising event that we've been planning for the past two years.
We decided to take advantage of the marketing potential of the Mayan calendar, which is set to end on December 21 at 11:10 a.m.
The day before this event, on December 20 at 21:00, three concerts will start in Prague, Brno and Ostrava.
They will end, roughly speaking, when the May calendar ends on the Pacific island of Kiribati, which has a time zone 12 hours ahead of ours.
Whose idea was that?
It was my idea at first, and then we worked on it with our artist Gonzaga Augusta.
Not only do we want to build up enough positive energy to prevent the end of the world, but we also want to think with the public about what kind of world we're going to pass on to our children.
To celebrate the end of the May calendar, we have created a unique collection of shoes, T-shirts, bags and original doomsday keys that you can buy on www.e-tap.cz and support.
The Tap Tap band, along with other musicians, also performed an anti-doomsday anthem called "The End of the World Is Cancelled".
Will the anthem that YouTube listeners already love be played at these benefit concerts?
Of course, in the end, if it works out and the world doesn't end.
It's sung by all the performers at all the concerts at the same time.
The anthems will also be broadcast live on Czech television.
The lyrics were written and performed by Tomáš Ganák, who also performs Xindl X...
How did you get involved with them?
We also work with other figures in Czech cultural life, as we hold many charity events and concerts.
We're trying to actively engage them in these projects.
It turns out a lot of people like working with us, they're interested.
What's the proceeds from the apocalypse concert going to do?
To purchase equipment for the STUDEO barrier-free education center, we have been working with the non-governmental organization Tap at the Edellichka Institute for six years.
Teachers regularly visit students at the school and hold fun and interesting activities with them.
Students themselves don't have the means to go to the teachers, and we try to give them that opportunity.
As part of the project to add to the Edlichka Institute, we will build a separate building in the future, which we will move into with this project.
Each concert will feature several musical groups and performers.
