Next year we'd love to do a show at the Czech National House in New York, and I personally, if we're in the U.S., I'd love to do a show in Washington and Chicago.
You have big plans for the outside world. You've performed in Madrid, Brussels, London and Moscow.
The Tap Tap is a group of people with disabilities.
How do you handle the road in terms of organization and logistics?
It's not as scary as it seems at first glance.
We have five contestants in electric wheelchairs, their wheelchairs have to travel in the luggage compartment, plus a lot of cargo and tool crates.
However, we managed to do it without any problems, and Czech Airlines ČSA and British Airways were always very prepared for us, which surprised me many times.
Even in Moscow, where we recently returned, everything went smoothly.
Traveling abroad allows you to compare different countries in terms of accessibility, public attitudes towards people with disabilities, and so on.
What have you encountered so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other countries where everything is functioning better than we do, in Russia we have seen that the east is still at the baseline.
Moscow has many barriers compared to Prague, and it is still a freakish place to be able to move around in an electric wheelchair in the city center.
And it's not about the mundane things like giving way to a disabled person in an elevator.
Fortunately, there are already NGOs that are trying to bring attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And what, on the contrary, are we supposed to be constantly catching up to?
There are a lot of things that are way behind the times.
But it's important to note that improvement and improvement always depends on the efforts of the people involved.
In London and Madrid, it's perfectly normal for people with severe disabilities to be able to walk around the streets, go to the bathroom, go to a museum, go anywhere.
It's not very common for people with disabilities to be active in the community, and we're a little ahead of them with The Tap Tap!
Public respect or open borders are one thing, but the moment we have a famous athlete, artist, actor, politician or lawyer, that's when things really start to change.
So far, these are isolated cases of people with strong wills.
The Tap Tap is very popular now, but back to two years ago, in 1998, what made you start it?
I went to the Edellich Institute as a tutor, and I was surrounded by many young people who wanted to do something.
And since I'm a musician and play saxophone, I organized an interesting music club with a colleague.
Well, as our host Ladia Angelovich says, it got a little out of hand.
Has it only become popular in recent years, or am I confusing something?
It's true, we were helped by the fact that we started to join famous singers and actively work on the promotion of the band.
We've come to the conclusion that work that nobody can evaluate is essentially like it doesn't exist.
Thanks to the European Union's funding, we can afford qualified teachers, equipment and so on.
Did you have a goal to promote The Tap Tap so well?
From the very beginning, I felt their potential in their ability to do something extraordinary.
Show business is full of things that imitate each other.
It's logical, everything new is taken with a grain of salt, and it lasts a long time.
There are very few rare things, but I would venture to say that Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression a person has of us is of course pity, it's natural...
But this pity is completely unnecessary, because people with disabilities are not all suffering and abandoned individuals that we should pity.
They are people who can live a full life and thrive, of course, only if they have the resources.
I say that if people with disabilities do something, it's a change not just for them, but for society.
Did your success depend on being the strict leader that many people think you are?
If we want to do a good job, we must be firm in many things and maintain a certain amount of discipline.
But I think it's okay.
Some people come to us with a romantic vision and fly in the air, and when they find out that they have to go to rehearsals twice a week, they have to go to prep classes and spend a lot of time on the road, they lose their enthusiasm very quickly.
But that's what happens to any group that wants to work and achieve something.
The Tap Tap currently has twenty members.
How many were there in early 1998?
There's only one Ladia Angelovich.
We're an open group, people come and go, it's impossible to prevent.
For those who have the will and the willpower, our doors are always open.
