Poland and space.
Last week, at a meeting of the European Space Agency's ministers, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of the European Space Agency as the second country from the former Eastern Bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on September 12, 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and has been actively involved in a number of ESA projects over the years.
But Poland's journey into space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in space travel, but this was not always understood.
I'll remind you, for example, of the lecture by A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933, presented at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory ideas from his groundbreaking work "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (1905-born) left the audience indifferent, after a few years, Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Peeltry and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966), mentioned earlier, later became a great proponent of astronomy and space exploration.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned cosmonaut, and his contribution was recognized in part by the naming of a crater on the far side of the Moon after him.
In 1925 a railway drezin equipped with a rocket engine was built in Poland.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remains unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It's not even clear if the missile was meant to accelerate or to brake the cart.
Information about this dressing is known only from the press of the time.
From 1933 on, the Polish artillery began to think about rocket arrows.
The research was carried out by the Section of Weapons Technology in cooperation with professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Mokzitski.
The surviving materials show that the research has reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of the German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photoelectric fighter rocket was proposed by engineer Rogozinsky, and the following year the work "Air rocket torpedo and aviation rocket bomb" by author Leliv-Kzivoblotsky was published.
Both designs were developed for military use with rocket engines.
Before the war, all projects of military use of rocket technology were undertaken by the Temporary Scientific-Consultative Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of its work ended due to the outbreak of war.
The next scientific work devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The society was first mentioned in the November 1954 issue of the journal "Problems", which published four volumes of articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that would be engaged in space exploration.
At that time, the development of artificial satellites was already in full swing, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautics Society (POA) has been trying to join the International Astronautics Federation (founded in 1951), and already in the autumn of the POA became its effective member.
And the following year, the first chairman of the PFA, Kazimeg Zarankevich (1902-1959) became the vice chairman of the International Astronaut Federation.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956 the POA has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful meteorological rocket RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna), which became the first Polish rocket to perform scientific research.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The missile, capable of a range of 1,800 m, was about 80 cm long and weighed less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959 two-stage RM-2 rockets were tested in the Bledovo desert.
This missile was about 1.4 meters long and its weight was about 11.5 kg.
The next version of the rocket was already capable of doing real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket could cover 14.5 km, and its task was to observe high winds.
But in 1962 further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type rockets was the Meteor-1, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage rocket, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (designated as Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the chamber for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A had a space of 0.4 liters, the Meteor-1B had 0.34 liters, and the Meteor-1C had 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Aviation Institute was developing the Meteor-2 rocket, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket, with a launch weight of 380 kg, was capable of delivering a 10 kg payload to a height of about 60 km.
Later versions of the Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 were built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's accession to KOSPAR (the Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the national KOSPAR committee two years later.
In addition, within the framework of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in space exploration on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 the Polish pilot Miroslav Germanashevsky became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
