Szabo: "Germans should play a bigger role"
Germany abstained in the vote on recognizing Palestine.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on U.S.-European relations, Berlin is balancing on a narrow diplomatic path.
Deutsche Welle: Earlier this week, Germany first made it clear that it would vote against the Palestinians' application for observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained from the vote.
Why? Why?
Stefan Szabo: Germany does not support the Israeli actions in Gaza.
Germany must be careful now about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I think she doesn't support the American position either.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the uprising in Libya in March 2011, Germany also abstained from voting on the no-fly zone.
NATO eventually made the offer.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear stand on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, from the policy which the United States, so to speak, was leading, to the German foreign policy itself.
The situation is further complicated by the lack of a common policy among Europeans.
Thus, the Germans are again caught between two fronts.
They're expected to play a more independent role, but they're not used to it.
I believe they are just getting a feel for their role, but they are on their way to a more "normal" foreign policy.
The kind of foreign policy that France or Britain have.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German perspective?
It is a willingness to take a position in our national interest that is independent of the position of the United States or our European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are very different from those of other major powers, and Germany must therefore defend its interests.
Did these economic interests influence the position in the Middle East conflict and the vote at the UN?
First, Germany has major markets in the Middle East, particularly in the Persian Gulf.
So she needs to be careful not to offend the public and the elites in the Arab countries.
Either way, it's playing a role.
But I wouldn't put too much pressure on it, it's not a one-way street.
But in any case, it plays a big part in the German calculations.
Did Germany hurt its relationship with the United States by abstaining from important decisions like the vote on Palestine?
I'm sure that in Europe and even in the United States, there is a predominant understanding of the German position.
So I don't think it was as dramatic a blow as the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect.
It is a signal that it should be taken seriously as an international player and that its interests should be taken into account.
There are different opinions in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The United States, on the other hand, has been clear in its veto.
Is there a difference of opinion between the United States and many European countries?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I believe that the Obama administration has a deep understanding of the European position.
But given the local political situation, the government cannot, of course, openly take such a position.
I believe that the substantial differences of opinion are not at all as significant as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you'll see that Obama is not very happy with Netanyahu's policies.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the United States on the one hand and its position as a key partner in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little easier for the Germans if there was a unified, consistent European policy, but that's not the case now.
So they cannot speak within the framework of a broader approach and are forced to act instead based on their own vision of the situation.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I think that Germany will take a leading role in the development of a common European position in the future.
It's not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties to Israel.
It's always been a sensitive subject.
But I think the Germans understand that they have to play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it not take on a really major role?
Or is the lead still hard for Germany?
Germany is not yet used to this, it is still always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, it is still difficult to play a significant role.
Take, for example, the euro crisis - every time Germany takes a leading role, there are all sorts of anti-German sentiments.
It's not easy for the Germans to handle.
Actually, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
In this respect, Germany is in a much worse position than the United States.
She has to take into account the many different neighbors and opinions, and that's not easy.
So the influence of the United States in European politics is constantly declining, but at this point, the EU is not filling the vacuum, so who is left?
The Germans will just have to play a bigger role.
Even if you don't like it, or it's unpleasant, or it's just making you feel unloved, that's life!
Steffen Szabo is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute where academics and political scientists from Europe and North America collaborate to study the problems of the transatlantic community.
In addition, Szabo is a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Trademark protection in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese"
Armani is a world-famous brand, Polo Ralph Lauren is too.
But what is Armani Polo?
It's a completely registered name in China, which has nothing to do with the companies that gave it its name.
However, it will be protected until the original names are sued.
But even then, it's not clear if they'll be able to defend their rights.
"It's getting harder and harder for foreigners to protect their trademarks in China", says Thomas Patloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing, which specializes in trademark infringement in the Far East.
I get a new case like this on my desk every week.
For example, a copycat may add a few letters to a trademark.
So Gucci becomes Lu-Gucci, and instead of Prada, you can register Prada-Kny.
German companies, such as sports goods manufacturer Puma, are being legally copied in the same way.
Patloch opens a file with records from the trademark office in Beijing.
On September 14, 2010, a Chinese company registered the Zegna DF Puma trademark, an artificial name that also used the name of the Ermenegildo Zegna fashion house.
The fact that the Chinese are world champions in copying and infringing on intellectual property rights is well known.
In large cities, there are department stores that sell almost exclusively counterfeit goods.
But Patloch's case is not that, and he is opposed to Chinese companies being given a license from the trademark office to use a name that is already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call it a ban minpai, a passenger car.
This word is associated with "ban daquan".
That's what they call a woman who goes after rich men.
Chinese authorities deny any responsibility
"It's hurting business and it needs to be tackled", Patloch said.
"The brand is fading, the unique position is lost, the image is suffering very badly".
The financial losses and legal costs in the affected industries are estimated to be in the millions, especially in the case of expensive copied products.
According to market research firm CLSA, China is the third largest and fastest growing luxury goods market with annual sales of 15 billion euros.
However, removing questionable trademarks is difficult and expensive.
The process can take up to nine years, with no clear outcome.
Patloch tells of cases in which the court rejected lawsuits because the name was "market reality" after a long time.
If the plaintiff is unlucky, he may even have to pay the plagiarist for damaging his trademark in China, says Patloch.
Sometimes it's the law of the jungle.
There are also famous cases of graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a legal dispute with construction machinery manufacturer Sany, an enterprise that had recently acquired concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
So the Chinese still have the right to use the Mercedes star-like emblem.
The company that bought Volvo Geely initially used a blue-white logo, reminiscent of BMW; the process was successful, Geely had to change it.
Fashion goods maker Lacoste lost in China to imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore, whose famous crocodile looked the other way.
The Chinese authorities do not consider themselves to be responsible.
The CTMO trademark office in Beijing confirms that in 2010 there were difficulties due to a lack of staff and equipment in the premises.
But last year saw a "return to normalcy from a workplace emergency".
The number of unresolved objections decreased by 22 percent.
Nearly 57,000 such cases were closed, a 75 percent increase over last year.
Still, 81,500 claims are still pending in the department.
It costs a lot to fight it.
As is often the case in China, the numbers are impressive.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
This is a record and means that China has topped the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth time in a row, the ministry said.
The same is true of the total number of valid trademarks, only 5.5 million.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan of fees were paid.
Simply put, this means that each registration costs an average of 1,280 yuan or 160 euros.
The cost of protesting is far greater, as the case of the German family-owned company Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the company has been fighting a Chinese plagiarist.
The Germans succeeded in eliminating their illegal production of counterfeit car parts.
However, the imitator secured the Chinese rights to the Freudenberg trademark.
This was a mistake on his part, since surnames are not protected in Germany, says Hannho Wentzler, chairman of Freudenberg Chemical Specialities in Munich.
And the CTMO trademark office has rejected the Munichers' claim.
True, Freudenberg won both subsequent trials, but the other side continues to fight until now.
We need to be vigilant .
The matter is now before the Supreme Court.
Wentzler hopes to bring the case to a successful conclusion and praises the courts' professionalism.
But he also says: "The process is extremely expensive and takes a lot of time, money, and nerve".
Internal costs are hardly accounted for, the firm's archives even had to go through records from a century ago to provide evidence.
Five years ago Freudenberg offered the opposing side "a large six-figure sum in euros" for a settlement, but to no avail.
"It's clear how expensive this is", says Wentzler.
The dangers of the Far East threaten to spill over into Europe.
Especially if the copycats register unprotected trademarks.
For example, a Chinese manufacturer in Germany wanted to register the name Freudenberg for shoes and leather goods.
The concern has long stopped production in these areas, but it has managed to prevent registration.
"You have to be on guard", says Wentzler.
Both he and Patloch advise German companies to be very careful with China.
Rather than relying on international trademark laws, foreigners should "register anything worth protecting in China", says Wentzler.
Otherwise, it could cost a lot more than registration.
Indeed, if Freudenberg loses the last act of his trademark drama, he will have to pay the opposing party royalties for his own name, Wentzler explains.
Otherwise, we'll be pushed out of the market in a controversial segment.
