Monday night, in the music hall of the Institute of Medical Psychology in Heidelberg, the Imbongis' choir rehearses a new song.
Fifty choir members, ranging in age from 23 to 69, came to the rehearsal, from a human genetics specialist to a janitor.
Om'Obani is a complex song, with each voice having a different text, and in a completely foreign language: Zulu, spoken by 11 million people in South Africa, Botswana, Lesotho, Malawi, Mozambique and parts of Swaziland.
Help for self-help
According to the United Nations AIDS program, there are an estimated 34 million people worldwide living with HIV.
Of these, 23.5 million live in southern Africa.
There are 245,000 AIDS orphans in Swaziland.
More than 40 percent of the population is HIV-positive.
Voices for Africa has found leaders in Germany for 180 AIDS orphans in Essien Village.
70 of them are in a school that prepares them for further education.
For 15 or 20 euros a month, you can take over the chef's job.
It guarantees the child money for school, school uniform and a daily hot lunch at the Gogo Center.
Imbongyi is Zulu for storyteller or praiser.
This room doesn't speak Bantu fluently, but they can sing.
For nearly a decade, the choir has been learning songs in this foreign soft language and even occasionally returns them to their original home in southern Africa.
For some 5,500 miles [8,733 km] from Heidelberg, in the northwest of the Kingdom of Swaziland, lies the village of Esitjeni, which depends on the voices of the German choir.
Forty percent are infected .
There are about 2,000 people living there, some still in simple huts made of clay and straw, and many children.
