According to Mr. Peña Nieto's opponents, he was at best described as having failed to address the issue of female murder during his time as governor.
At worst, his administration is accused of ignoring the problem.
Irineia Buendia, a resident of a concrete house like most in this dilapidated neighborhood, is having a hard time holding back her tears as she shows me photos of her deceased daughter, Mariana Luna.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that her roommate killed her.
"When I got to her house, it looked like her body had been washed", recalls Buendia.
There were signs of a beating, and the body was already bruised.
Mariana's mother tells the story, and her daughter's portrait looks at us from the wall, where it hangs next to a crucifix that has only one word on it: justice.
That, they say, is what this family was denied.
"The state officials treated me like an old gossip, a disgruntled troublemaker.
They want people to just take what they say and shut up.
But it's wrong, it's not right, especially when there are so many violations and flaws", she says.
By taking the presidential apron on Saturday, President Peña Nieto will take on a difficult responsibility with her.
Tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violent crime in the past six years, and the new president has promised to make addressing the problem a priority during his term.
"I hope he will be exactly the same president as he was as governor", says Olvera, a PRI congressman from Valle de Bravo.
But that's what the families of the victims in Ciudad Nesa fear most.
Bradley Manning has no complaints of ill-treatment, the prosecution says.
Prosecutors are trying to refute Bradley Manning's claims about poor conditions in custody.
The hearing focused on Manning's time in the military prison at Quantico, Virginia.
The defense is demanding that the case be closed on the grounds that Manning's conditions were harsh.
The U.S. Army is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution sought to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest leak of classified material in U.S. history, failed to take advantage of the many opportunities to complain about the mistreatment he said he had suffered while in military prison.
During cross-examination at a pre-trial hearing in Fort Meade, Maryland, military prosecutor Major Ashden Fein stated that records of Manning's weekly visits by prison officials during his nine months in Quantico, Virginia, contained no complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination of the defense's motion to dismiss Manning's case on the grounds that the conditions of his confinement were cruel and sufficient punishment in themselves was held the day after Manning stated that while in custody, he intended to commit suicide.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were later published online on the WikiLeaks website.
WikiLeaks has not confirmed that Manning was the source.
During Friday's hearing, prosecutor Fein reviewed with Manning the reports that were completed after Manning was visited by administration officials during his time in Quantico, where he was held in strict conditions from July 2010 to April 2011.
During the visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When prosecutor Fein asked on Friday about the reports, Manning admitted that he considered the prison administration's treatment of him "excellent" and the general conditions of detention "very professionally organized".
The reviewed reports contain no complaints of ill-treatment, despite Manning being asked explicitly about the conditions of his detention, Fein claims.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns orally about these problems and that administration officials who had visited him had discussed them with him and said they would address them, but had not recorded this in writing.
"They wrote 'no problems' (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn't mean I didn't bring it up in the conversation", Manning says.
A military judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not complained of mistreatment in January 2011 during a committee hearing on suicidal thoughts he had expressed in writing months earlier.
Manning replied that during that hearing he wanted to get his "trauma prevention" regime lifted and his conditions eased.
Military officials explained that the limited detention regime - a level lower than the suicide prevention surveillance regime - was introduced to protect the prisoner as well as the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I was fine, that they would cancel the injury prevention regime... that my standard of living would improve, from my point of view", Manning explained.
On Thursday, Manning testified about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to a prison at the Naval Base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said that he had suicidal thoughts in Kuwait and that he had once fainted in the heat.
He explained that it's very difficult psychologically when you're not allowed to know how your destiny is decided and what's going on in the outside world.
"My world has shrunk to the size of Camp Arifjan, to the size of my prison", Manning said Thursday.
- I thought I was going to die in this cage".
While at Quantico, Manning, he said, spent most of his time in a small cell - at least 21 hours, and often more than 23 hours a day - in complete solitude.
Manning reports that he was only allowed to leave behind a mattress, a blanket, slippers, a few items of clothing and glasses.
He says he tried to move because sleeping or even just lying down during the day was against the rules.
Manning said that during his sleep, he was constantly being struck by light coming from outside the chamber.
If the guards didn't see his face when he turned in bed at night, he said they woke him up and made him turn on his back.
Manning's lawyer filed a formal objection to Manning's mistreatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge questioned Manning about a statement he made during his testimony on Thursday that after being forced to sleep naked in his cell at Quantico one night, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates at the morning checkpoint.
Manning said he was unable to cover himself with a blanket during the inspection.
In response to questions from the judge on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard's order that he should throw away a blanket he could cover himself with, but admitted that no one had directly ordered him to throw it.
On Thursday, Manning said he had been forced to sleep naked the night before because he tried to show the officer that he was no danger to himself.
Manning reported telling an officer he could have used a rubber band or a pair of panties to injure himself, but he didn't.
That night, according to Manning, his underwear, slippers and glasses were taken from his cell.
His lawyers hope the judge will at least take into account his experience in prison and substantially reduce his sentence if Manning is found guilty by a military court, which is due to begin hearing his case early next year.
The defense said it planned to offer Manning a plea to lesser charges and challenge the other charges as excessive.
The hearing is scheduled to resume this weekend, with the prosecution expected to insist that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was held at Quantico under the strictest detention rules.
Among the charges brought against Manning are aiding and abetting an enemy, illegal facilitation of the publication of data on the Internet, transmission of information concerning national defense, and theft of public property or documents.
If convicted on all counts, he could face life in prison.
My crisis of national self-determination is the story of a Mexican-American.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities to fulfill themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the people of the difficult times.
Ruben Navarrete believes that Mexican Americans are torn between two cultures.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked down the arrivals corridor, approached the border checkpoint, and froze.
The signs indicated two lines: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the other for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood there for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California, and I've been called a Mexican all my life.
It's just a conventional name, just like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish and my friends in New York call themselves Italian.
Later, I focused on the complex construction of "Mexican American".
But I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather's homeland, there was no need for nouns or complex constructions.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than a native speaker's, and I can't shake the American accent.
So I got my American passport and stood in line for the Extranjeros.
I remembered this story a few days ago when the newly elected president of Mexico, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
The agenda was the usual meeting of presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Peña Nieto has been eager to talk about the upswing in the Mexican economy, which will now allow Mexicans to stay in Mexico with equal success, instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to make a partnership deal with the U.S. and Canada and create a sort of North American trade bloc like the European Union.
President Peña Nieto has also promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no concrete proposals have been made.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is a difficult and old-fashioned matter.
Most Americans never thought that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and, under the gunpowder of its leaders, forced them to give up half their territory.
But Mexicans think in centuries, not minutes, and they see reminders of those events in everything.
So the moment any US statesman speaks a word of criticism of Mexico, the press and the elite of Mexican society immediately complain that the Americans are encroaching on the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the descendants of Montezuma are full of war.
The most difficult is Mexico's relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican Americans living in the United States.
You want to talk about resentment?
There's enough of them.
There are winners and losers in Mexico, people who find opportunities in this country, and those who don't.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio, there are so many people of Mexican descent for one reason only: at some point in their family history, someone -- father or grandfather -- was unable to fulfill themselves in Mexico and was forced to go north.
Most often, they were a certain type of Mexican -- dark-skinned, poorly educated, poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember it.
In Mexico, they see it differently.
Our lives today are the American dream, we went to good schools and got good jobs, but we must remember that even that dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national identity is confused and unclear, but we know which country to consider our own.
The United States of America.
We also know that most of the Mexican elite and ruling class don't like us.
We're going to answer them the same.
They see us as a reminder of humiliating defeats and treat us as second-class citizens, as fake Mexicans.
We don't speak Spanish well enough, and our ties to Mexico aren't strong enough.
Our very existence is explained to them by failure.
If our ancestors had made it in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
We wouldn't be behind the silk curtain, finding a life in the United States, but losing our spiritual connection.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and came to the United States legally as a child, and that reminds me that there are certain tensions between real Mexicans and Mexican Americans -- Mexicans are more aware of their national identity, and Mexican Americans are offended by it.
She's a U.S. citizen and she thinks she belongs in both countries.
At the same time, many of the Mexican Americans I know don't feel like they belong to either of them.
We listen to a Mexican band called Los Tigres del Norte, but we also like Bruce Springsteen.
Getting the best of both worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
In Mexico, we are Americans.
And in the U.S., we're called Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relationship is not already complicated enough, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to rebuild relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican Americans to act as ambassadors for Mexico and represent its interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends what a wonderful country it is and how great it is to visit, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, of course.
It's not gonna work.
Too much resentment in the past.
And given the gap between rich and poor, the rampant corruption and drug trafficking, many of us don't think this country is that great.
I'm sorry, but you guys can handle this on your own, amigos.
And that's fair.
If some Mexicans still can't forgive the United States for what they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Mexican Americans still resent what was done to their relatives in Mexico recently.
I know.
I guess we have more in common than I thought.
Old battles in the new Middle East
The ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could be a fragile foundation for future peace
Is there a lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
Another round of bloodshed leads to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
The usual, pointless arguments about who started it all; the ruins of many buildings; the killing of more than 140 Palestinians, mostly civilians, and six Israelis; the first time in the conflict that rockets fired from Gaza have hit the outskirts of Israel's capital Tel Aviv and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But even as Israelis and Palestinians are hopelessly caught up in their eternal conflict, the Middle East is changing.
This can be viewed in different ways, but the events of the Arab Spring have turned many established realities into a rebellious storm, and Palestinians and Israelis have not been able to stay out of the whirlwind that has rocked the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will be even more bloody than before.
However, there is reason for hope in the path of salvation.
A War Without Winners
At first glance, the situation is not one of optimism.
Even if the ceasefire signed on November 21 is implemented, this week's clashes have only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist movement Hamas, which came to power in Gaza in 2007, will claim that they forced Israel to retreat despite the losses they suffered.
Despite the fact that some of the group's leaders have been killed and 1.7 million people are trapped in one of the most densely populated and troubled corners of our planet, Israel has not been able to destroy Hamas.
Hamas is actually building its popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is on their side.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new influential and wealthy friends.
The resurgent regional leader Turkey, once Israel's closest ally among Muslim countries, has come out in support of Hamas; followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamic Persian Gulf states.
Hamas's triumphant supporters claim to have created an Islamist crescent around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, where the militant Hezbollah group rules, to Syria, where increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are about to topple Bashar Assad's government, and on to Jordan, where the king's rule is threatened by Hamas allies.
The most significant change in the balance of power in the region occurred on Israel's southern borders, in the most populous and important Arab country, Egypt, where the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood movement has strengthened under President Mohamed Morsi.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was ousted in 2011, was a secular dictator who paid little attention to Hamas's support.
The Muslim Brotherhood, by contrast, is an organization much like Hamas, and its leaders are more populist.
In future diplomatic settings, Hamas could become a significant player whose voice even Israel and America cannot silence.
Meanwhile, Israel's hardliners will come to the opposite conclusion.
Militarily, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli Iron Dome missile defense system has justified its cost and successfully destroyed many of the Hamas missiles launched.
The citizens of Israel can sleep soundly, at least for a while.
As for diplomacy, the US has remained steadfast; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for the latest round of violence.
Another important factor is Israel's economic prosperity, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, which has largely ignored the peace process.
Although some 30 Israelis have been killed by rockets fired from Gaza since 2004, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, in part by building a wall that reaches into the West Bank - a large part of the unrecognized Palestinian state - and protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions under international law.
Prime Minister Netanyahu's position, whose Likud party - in preparation for the January 22 elections - has teamed up with even more aggressive conservatives led by Avigdor Lieberman, is quite convenient.
What's the point of giving the Palestinians their own state?
If you give them all the power in the West Bank, won't they start firing rockets at Israel from there, like their brothers in Gaza?
It's better to keep them against the wall and to suppress any attempt to raise their heads.
The hardliners may win, but their calculations may be disproved by the Arab Spring.
While the Islamists who come to power in Egypt and elsewhere may not have the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be domestic issues.
Israel's defense budget is larger than all of its Arab neighbors put together.
Unleashing a war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of Egyptian President Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on a ceasefire, is a good sign and could signal the beginning of change.
Israel, no less, must consider the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic change comes to the Arab world, depriving the Palestinians of their right to self-determination is a time bomb that will explode in the Israeli-occupied territories, like the bus that blew up in Tel Aviv this week.
The repression is already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect - the growth of the Arab population - is only exacerbating these problems.
The bloody operations that are carried out every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement are paying off with growing international discontent.
Both sides need an outside push.
The only solution that remains is one that is being relentlessly called for by sane people on both sides, and by much of the rest of the world and our paper: the creation of two states and the ceding of territory by Israel in exchange for security.
There is hope, not too great in the short term, that a ceasefire will allow other countries to influence the parties more effectively.
Egypt, which has long since decided to cut off arms supplies to Gaza, as well as Turkey and Qatar, are in a better position than ever to persuade Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state, agreed since 1967 with the exchange of territories and the shared use of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile Hamas and Fatah.
This would do more to create a Palestinian state than the upcoming UN vote, which could result in the recognition of a virtual state of Palestine.
President Obama has a role to play in getting Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own plan for a peace settlement.
After returning to the White House, he still shows little interest in getting involved.
It's a disastrously shortsighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
This is only possible if there is a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, a law on uniform packaging for cigarettes has come into force.
Warnings about the dangers of smoking and images of diseased body parts are contrasted on the gloomy green boxes, which are the same for all brands of cigarettes.
Australia's first-ever law on the uniform packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products has been passed, replacing the logos and colour schemes of different brands with the same gloomy olive box with gruesome images of sick body parts and children whose health is being undermined by their parents' smoking.
Aside from the different pictures and signs warning of the dangers of smoking, the only difference between the packages, which will be mandatory this Saturday, is the brand names, which are printed in the same small print.
These are the world's strictest conditions for tobacco packaging.
The federal government says the measure is designed to discourage youth from smoking by stripping the harmful habit of its fashionable status.
The basis for this decision was the results of studies that showed that people who did not start smoking before the age of 26 never became smokers in 99 out of 100 cases.
"It is clear that even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through the packaging", explains Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, referring to studies that show that, for example, the crown in a logo is associated with the idea of a princess.
Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world, so the changes will not affect the profits of multinational corporations, but other countries are considering similar measures.
The tobacco industry strongly opposed the law.
Tobacco companies claim that this will only increase the share of the black market, where cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
"This bill will have a serious impact that is different from what its proponents envisioned", says Scott McIntyre, a British American Tobacco representative in Australia.
Counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will be putting more of these products on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the other hand, new laws are a business opportunity.
Sandra Ha of the small family-owned company Zico Import Pty Ltd claims that demand for cigarette packs and silicone cases that hide nasty images on the packaging has risen sharply (from virtually zero) since two months ago when companies such as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a case in Australia's high court, where they tried to appeal the law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about 6,000 products to wholesale businesses and is expecting a new batch.
It's a good business for us.
A potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures is, according to experts, the popularity of social networks among the population to which these measures are aimed.
After a series of laws passed in Australia that made television advertising for cigarettes and their promotion of sporting events illegal, and prohibited vendors from displaying cigarettes in a prominent place, tobacco advertising moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from posting ads online, but it cannot restrict foreign sites.
"If you're a tobacco seller and you've only got this one little loophole, the idea of advertising your product online may seem very tempting", explains Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes a rise in the number of reviews of trademarks written by supposedly ordinary users on social media such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question is, is this really the work of a common citizen who loves Marlboro so much that he spared no time and effort to make the video, or is it the work of an advertising company?
The Australian branch of British American Tobacco claims that the industry is now more concerned with adapting to the new regulations than with advertising.
The tobacco industry has even taken steps such as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: these countries are filing complaints at the World Trade Organization, claiming that trade has been unfairly restricted, despite the fact that all of these countries have very little trade with Australia.
The WTO decision is expected by mid-2013.
According to Tanie Plibersek, the government has been discussing with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada became the first country to mandate the posting of tobacco warning photos.
Now this rule is adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey, and Ukraine.
Tougher laws are being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia are demonstrating a lack of compliance.
I'm not affected by these pictures.
I'm just not paying attention.
"You just take out a cigarette and put a pack in your pocket", explains Victor El Haig, who buys cigarettes with a picture of a mouth tumor on the pack.
Honestly, the only thing that can make me quit is my little girl.
James Yu, manager of King of the Pack tobacco store in Sydney's inner city, claims that the same packaging has made it difficult to arrange the products on the shelves
"It used to take me an hour to unload a new batch, but now it takes me four hours", he complains.
"If the government had taken over and banned cigarettes altogether, we would have said, 'What do we do, it's over, we close the store,'" he says, his hands up.
In a world of electronic networks and constant connections, it's not so bad to get bored.
On that Thanksgiving, I was suddenly stuck at the airport for five hours because our plane had a mechanical malfunction and had to be replaced with the plane we were waiting for.
So I had plenty of time to think about the nature of boredom.
I'm not gonna lie to you.
Half a day at the airport waiting for a flight is really boring, and there's not much help in books, magazines, iPhones, or even duty-free shops.
Recently, however, a growing number of scientists and child-development experts have spoken in favor of boredom.
They say that in certain situations, it's not so bad for us and our children to be bored.
It forces the brain to focus on interesting, related topics, which may actually promote creativity.
And in our modern world, where we're all constantly in front of a screen, the benefits of boredom are getting away from us.
Maybe we should strive for boredom?
I'm not sure.
And at the same time, no.
We'll get back to that.
I used to think, like many people, that boredom was a relatively recent invention, when people had more free time.
That is not the case, says Peter Tui, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary, Canada, and author of Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
"In fact, boredom has a very old history", he says.
On the walls of Pompeii, Latin inscriptions on boredom date back to the first century.
But the question remains, how do we understand boredom?
The problem, says John D. Eastwood, an associate professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, is that the perception and perception of boredom has often changed.
After reviewing research on the subject and asking a group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: Boredom is when people "want to do something but are unable to do something that would give them satisfaction".
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person does not do something he would like to do.
I don't want to do anything with apathy.
The main cause of boredom, he says, is "attention loss and the associated mood swings and the feeling that time is passing by slowly".
Boredom can sound very similar to depression.
However, despite the possible link between these conditions, Professor Eastwood argues, homesick people see the causes of problems in the world and in circumstances, whereas depressed people see the problems in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored when in fact we just have trouble concentrating.
In their study, "The Unemployed Mind: Defining Boredom in terms of Attention", published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues refer to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a voice recording a journal reading.
Some participants also heard loud, unrelated sounds from a television program in the next room, others heard the same sounds at such a low volume that they could hardly be distinguished, and a third group listened to only voice recordings without a separate sound track.
Those who listened to the TV at a low volume reported feeling bored, more often than others - having trouble concentrating, but not knowing why, and attributing it to boredom.
When we try to concentrate on a difficult or exciting task, distraction can be boring, says Mark J. Fenske, associate professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph, Ontario, and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when we do something uninteresting, "like looking at a stream of products on a conveyor belt in search of a marriage, distracting music can help us avoid boredom".
He goes on to say that it is thought that when people start rocking in a chair or drawing on a piece of paper, they are doing so out of boredom, but we now know that in fact, such actions simply help to keep them physically relaxed.
"Research has shown that children who are not restricted from walking and spinning learn better and remember more information than children who are required to sit still", claims Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at times - when our flight is delayed (as in my case), when we listen to a monotonous speech, when we watch a dull movie.
However, people differ in their tendency to be bored.
In the 1980's, researchers developed a "boredom scale" to measure these individual traits.
The scale uses questions and statements such as "A lot of what I have to do is monotonous and monotonous" or "I have too much to do, so I don't have time for anything".
Using questionnaires like these, researchers have found that boys are more likely than girls to be bored, says Steven Wodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, "especially when there are a variety of external stimuli".
However, teenagers in general are often bored.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he paged nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32% of teenagers said they were bored at school and during homework, and 23% said they were bored outside of school.
Only 3% of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what similar data on boredom would look like now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that "the tendency to be bored peaks during adolescence", largely because children and teens are not given the full freedom to choose what to do.
So back to my original question: Is boredom useful?
Sometimes not, because in extreme cases, research shows, it can lead people to engage in absurd and dangerous physical activities, risky gambling, or substance abuse in an attempt to escape boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have pondered the link between boredom and creativity, says Professor Wodanovich, who has devoted more than two decades to studying the problem.
"That's how our brain tells us to do something else; that's boredom", says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
But that same brain doesn't always know what to do.
If you're bored and you put that energy into playing guitar or cooking, you'll feel better.
However, if you start watching TV, you will only feel better for a while, and it will soon pass.
So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he will stop being bored, but he will not learn to deal with boredom on his own or to manage his time and activities in any other way, says Professor Fenske.
"And these self-regulatory skills are used in a variety of situations", he says.
Your child is not only learning to do things on his own, but he is also learning self-control in general.
I don't think boredom should be glorified.
But it's not a bad thing either.
Rather, we should learn to be comfortable even outside the continuous flow of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees with that.
"We see it as a need to get bored more often, when boredom is a very unpleasant, insatiable desire to do something meaningful", he says.
What people really want is to get out of their constant worries and just relax.
"In today's world", he says, "we are used to constantly over-stimulating our senses, and when silence comes, we are lost and do not know what to do".
It's not clear how the new marijuana legalization law will be enforced in Colorado.
Anthony Orosco, a 19-year-old soccer player and community college student in southeastern Colorado, has been charged with a criminal offense that will soon be perfectly legal throughout the state: possession of a small amount of marijuana and the pipe he smoked it in.
Mr. Orosco says that one day in September, he and some friends were in Lamar driving through the prairie near the Kansas border when they were stopped by police.
After a police officer found marijuana in his car, Mr. Orozco was subpoenaed for possession of narcotics and possession of a drug-use device - misdemeanors that each carry a $100 fine - and a court date was set.
"We are treated like criminals", says Mr. Orozco.
But is he a criminal?
As a result of the uncertainty that has persisted for weeks after Colorado voted to legalize recreational small-scale marijuana use, the decision of hundreds of small-scale court cases depends less on the law than on the venue.
Small marijuana charges are already being dropped in hundreds of cases here and in Washington state, which has taken similar action.
Police stations have already stopped charging people 21 and older for possession of small doses, which will only be considered legal once the law takes effect in a couple of weeks.
However, in more conservative districts of Colorado, prosecutors have decided to pursue existing marijuana cases and continue to prosecute for possession of the drug.
Meanwhile, some cities from the suburbs of Denver to the mountainous West are voting to ban new, state-licensed marijuana shops.
"It's all happening so fast, I don't even know what to expect", says Daniel J. Oates, police chief in Aurora, east of Denver.
Washington state regulators are also scratching their heads in disbelief.
They will have to formulate rules to determine how to license the cultivation, processing, distribution and sale of marijuana, and all this must be done by December 1, 2013.
They say that Colorado, for better or worse, is ahead of most other states in regulating marijuana, first for medical use and now for recreational use.
"Colorado has a more regulated market, so they're a good example", explains Brian E. Smith, a spokesman for the D.C. Alcohol Regulatory Commission.
But now, Mr. Smith admits, there is nothing more anyone can do than to put forward proposals and hope that they will work.
"We don't have a real precedent to go by", he says.
The Washington state bill, called I-502, will go into effect on December 6 and leave the state in a state of uncertainty for a year, with no state licensing system yet and the right to possess marijuana already legal.
And there are still some technical issues that need to be addressed during this time, like how to balance the state's "adequate access" policy for licensed marijuana with a ban on selling within 1,000 feet of schools, parks, playgrounds and kindergartens.
