I was expelled from Oxford because I was a conservative.
The persecution of university students for their beliefs did not begin today.
For as long as I can remember, I've dreamed of going to Oxford University.
My father and older brother both went to Oxford, and they described it as the best university in the world, a modern analogue of an ancient symposium, laying the two foundations of civilization -- freedom of thought and tolerance.
And yet, after two weeks of studying history at Worcester College, Oxford University, in the late '80s, I packed up and left, which resulted in the first real scandal of my life.
My father couldn't stand it and cried.
The friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed that I dropped out of college because I didn't like my classmates having sex in the next room.
The writer E. Norman Wilson joked that I left because I had to drink from the syrup cups.
It wasn't really that funny.
I ran away.
Yeah, I ran away because I was systematically poisoned and intimidated.
Not because of my rather unusual name or the fact that I went to a private school.
I was poisoned for one reason only, and in this glorious cradle of the Enlightenment, it looked like a barbaric and blind bigotry: my father, now deceased Woodrow Wyatt, was a famous adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I was a conservative myself.
You may ask, why bring it up now?
According to recent reports, a new generation of students with center-right views are being bullied in the same way.
This institutionalized and ever-growing hatred of conservative students in Oxford is so strong that last week a group of conservative students demanded the same protection for their rights as those afforded to disabled, sexual and ethnic minorities.
Conservatives at the Corpus Christi College student club in Cambridge say they are "often actively isolated, personally attacked and made to feel unwelcome" because of their political views.
They want to add an additional representative to the college's Equal Rights Committee to ensure freedom of expression.
Their situation was exacerbated by a recent BBC 2 documentary about student politics, Wonderland: Young, Smart and Right, which portrayed conservatives as eccentric and neo-Nazi.
The film featured Joe Cook, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Association, riding a Rolls-Royce, wearing a silver suit and a cane with a silver top hat.
In other universities, conservative students complain that they are being made "goats for the expense of higher tuition".
Luke Black, 20, vice-president of the Conservative Association at Nottingham University, said in an interview with the Sunday newspaper that "the university community is increasingly leaning to the left.
People who don't even know us assume that we are the brazen, unpunished children of rich parents".
Samuel Roberts, 21, a student at Corpus Christi College's history department, who was asked to step up his defence, called the atmosphere "uncomfortable", while Stephanie Cheryl, 19, the new president of Oxford University's Conservative Association, said the student club's attitude towards centre-righters had deteriorated significantly.
"This is a threat to both the atmosphere of intellectual discussion and simply to the normal life of the club members", she says.
For the first few weeks at Oxford, I wasn't just in the minority, I was alone.
I entered in September 1986, a shy, shy 18-year-old girl.
Oxford was racked with hatred of the Conservative Party.
A year earlier, the university voted to strip former student Margaret Thatcher of her honorary degree because of budget cuts to higher education.
Even the Stalinists would be uncomfortable in such an atmosphere.
In the first few days of my freshman week, when the students were getting to know each other and the teachers, I had a first-hand sense of what was ahead of me.
I didn't know that teachers not only looked the other way on bullying conservative students, but they were also happy to participate.
Political issues - the miners' strike, privatization, and the government's refusal to sanction the apartheid government in South Africa - were pouring through the wooden-panelled walls of the auditoriums.
My first seminar was to translate an 18th-century French text into English, and I wasn't prepared for what was to come.
"Miss Wyatt", said the teacher, now the late Harry Pitt, "please translate the first paragraph".
I had trouble getting the lyrics, so I got stuck.
Harry Pitt was a very bitter man with a face like a cake.
"Do the Thatcherites not learn French at all, or are they just not smart enough?" he asked.
The other students giggled.
I was in tears.
"I suggest you take some initial French lessons in your spare time, unless you're too busy hanging out", Pitt snarled.
I went back to my room completely unhappy.
That night at college, I was sitting alone at lunch; then someone patted me on the shoulder.
It was James, a second-year student in the English department who introduced himself as a member of the university's Conservative Association.
"I know who you are", he said amicably.
- Unfortunately, the facts are as follows:
Anyone suspected of sympathizing with the conservatives will be mocked.
It's not easy for me, and in your case, they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it's gonna be harder for you.
Most conservative freshmen pretend to be Labour".
Later, at the local pub, I cowardly tried to pretend.
I insisted that I didn't agree with everything Margaret Thatcher said.
The trick didn't work.
A first-year student of philosophy, politics and economics, who had himself studied at Eton, said: "You are the daughter of a fascist pig.
You are contagious".
The other students picked up on his words.
I was spoiled, dirty.
"How do conservatives have sex?" one of them asked.
- They're kicking each other, aren't they?"
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the repeal of the law in the 1960s.
Will I ever be able to live a normal life in Oxford?
Or do I have to meet with my fellow believers only under the cover of night?
Am I going to be forced to become a Labour member and hide my true beliefs?
The next three years seemed like hell, full of persecution and loneliness.
The only professor at my college who was open about his conservative views was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history.
He was hated not only for being a conservative, but also for being Thatcher's foreign policy adviser and one of her speechwriters.
He barely showed up at college.
He despised him for his provincialism, his pettyness, and his adherence to a Marxist-determinist view of history.
In 1997, he accepted a professorship at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
"You won't be happy here", he told me.
I started to travel to Oxford from my parents' home in London, trying to find refuge among relatives and unbiased friends in the capital.
I told my father I hated Oxford and explained why.
He didn't believe me.
During his studies in the forties, any political views were accepted.
"But it's the best university in the world", he said complainingly.
- They can't do that, except in the city of sleeping spires...
Even my Communist friends have always behaved impeccably".
His wet eyes were blurry.
"Do not make hasty decisions.
I'm sure it's just a joke.
You're gonna break my heart if you drop out".
I was exhausted from my constant trips to London and my emotional defenses were weak.
My friend, also a conservative, couldn't stand the pressure and gave up his beliefs.
The next week at the seminar, when another history teacher called me "enemy of the people" in all seriousness, I decided to do the same.
In my heart of shame, I admitted that my parents had brainwashed me and called them "old fools".
The respite was short.
The final nail in the coffin of my Oxford career was destined to be my father.
At the time, he wrote two columns a week for Rupert Murdoch's publications.
My door was locked.
I didn't go out, and five minutes later, my pursuers surrendered.
When they left, I packed my bags and took the first train to London.
