"Valentino prefers elegance to fame"
About the Valentino: Sewing Master exhibition that opened this week in London, ABC talks to Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza and other high-profile clients of the Italian designer.
Somerset House, former residence of Queen Elizabeth I, is the only place in the British capital worthy of hosting an exhibition about Valentino Garavani.
The designer acknowledged this at the opening of Valentino: Master of Sewing, a triumphant retrospective exhibition that brings together more than 130 high fashion dresses created by his "house" over the past 50 years.
"I love this palace", he says in his distinctive Italian accent.
This exhibition is the final part of a story whose only character is "il signor" Garavani, but it could not have been written without his famous clients.
Valentino has always felt fascinated by the rare and distant world of nobility.
The first hall of the exhibition, open until March 3, is filled with personal letters and photos signed by the most distinguished aristocrats, from Princess Salima Aga Khan to Lord Snowdon, including Marie Chantal, Princess of Greece, and Margaret, Princess of Great Britain.
Valentino shows these personal memories as trophies of his social rise: from a humble tailor from the northern Italian town of Voghera to the idol of the international "elite".
There's nothing wrong with being in love with the royal court.
"At least they don't put out their cigarette butts on your gorgeous carpet like some of the great pop stars do", says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza.
In the '60s and '70s, we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is a unique host who welcomes guests with generosity and elegance.
"We all really enjoyed coming to his shop in Gstaad", explains "Heine" Thyssen, a close friend of forgotten beauties like Marella Agnelli and Eugenia Niarchos.
Valentino always preferred elegance to fame.
And yet he is a star.
Valeria Mazza, representing Valentino
Argentine model Valeria Mazza is reminiscent of the charismatic fashion designer.
We went to his house for dinner one night, after the fashion show in the Plaza de España in Rome, many years ago.
Among the twenty guests were Sharon Stone and John F. Kennedy Jr.
Valentino's style was evident in everything -- every detail of his apartment, its decor, its food, its music.
"Valentino made each of his guests feel important and loved", recalls the top model, whose work with the designer began in 1995 during the Paris Fashion Week.
"He never goes out of style because his sketches are real works of art", she concludes.
The parade of the lineage
The life of Caravani is not a story of obsessions, but of love with complete reciprocity.
He likes people with good manners and high titles, and they like him.
One of the galleries at Somerset House has been transformed into a glamorous, sixty-meter-long podium that offers a role-change: the visitor takes the place of the models and must parade down the podium, gazing at the "spectators" from the dreams that shine with Valentino's masterpieces, such as the dress that Jacqueline Kennedy chose for her wedding to Aristotle Onassis, the suit that Monica Vitti used in The Night, or the wool and leather coat that belonged to Empress Farrah Diba.
The model audience includes names such as Sibylla of Luxembourg, Gloria von Turn und Taxis, Mette-Marit from Norway, Rosario from Bulgaria, and Sophia Habsburg.
Naty Abascal and the model, 2006
Many of these clients say that the first Valentine is like first love, "unforgettable".
I remember him well.
They were pants, a shirt, a vest and a jacket from the 1971-1972 autumn-winter collection.
"It was a gift he gave me", says Nati Abascal, one of the designer's muses.
"I prefer him to the rest because of his femininity, his great love for women, because he emphasizes our beauty", adds the former Duchess de Feria.
I really like the colors he uses, they're very bright and they're very good for his face.
The proportions are perfect.
Princess and fashion legislator Patricia della Giovanpaola d'Arenberg also cannot forget the first time she dressed as Valentino.
When I was a teenager living in Italy, I dreamed I'd have the age and the reason to wear one of his evening towels...
Finally, that hour came in the late 1990's.
I bought my first dress from Valentino to wear to a party at my cousin's castle, Prince Edward de Ligne.
It was a red dress, with a skirt with a skirt, a corsage in the fold, and a cut without braces.
"It was a dream come true", says Rodrigo d'Arenberg's widow.
"Valentino is fashion-deprived, his passion is timeless", explains this Italian aristocrat who lives between Paris, New York, and Buenos Aires.
Princess d'Arenberg keeps her holiday dresses from the designer with "maximum care... because a dress is not just a dress, it is also a collection of memories that accompany it".
The "King" of Fashion
The grand finale of the exhibition at Somerset House is Marie-Chantal Miller's wedding dress for her wedding to Pavlos of Greece in 1995.
It took four months of work and 25 "girls" (as the designer calls his seams) to make this garment of ivory-colored silk with pearl inlays, twelve different types of rings, and a four-and-a-half-meter-long strip.
According to journalist Susie Menkes, the greatest authority on the specialized press, the dress represents a milestone in late 20th-century high fashion, "the return of customers from the high world".
Deceived for years by the "lifestyle" of the elite, Valentino is now its best representative.
Knight of the Grand Cross (the highest ranking distinction in Italy), Knight of Labor, Commander of the Order of Arts and Letters, decorated with the Order of the Legion of Honor, Garavani has received as many honors as any of his client's spouses.
"I was always attracted by his refinement, his calmness, his neat and flawless appearance", recalls d'Arenberg.
I last saw him a month ago at a dinner party at the Musée d'Orsay.
He was at the table with Countess Jacqueline de Ribery, a great friend of mine.
"He was impeccable, there is no time for him".
If the princess says so...
The hardest job in the world: the miners from Kawah-Ijen
For four euros, Indonesian miners risk their lives and health by hauling 70 kilograms of sulfur onto the volcano's steep rocky trails
Some people think their jobs are hell, and some people literally work in hell.
Among them is Anto Vijaya, one of 400 miners who earn their living mining sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano on the eastern Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Antônio descends to the bottom of the crater, where sulfur gas rising from the Earth's depths freezes in contact with the air.
He chops off huge pieces of sulfur, which can weigh up to 170 pounds [70 kg], puts them in two bamboo baskets, wraps the baskets on his shoulders, and carries them up a steep rocky road.
It is only a quarter mile [250 m] to the top of the 8,930-foot-high [2,386 m] volcano, but exhausted truckers take more than 40 minutes to make a turtle-like ascent, struggling to keep their balance and carefully treading the path to avoid tripping and falling off a cliff.
They know that one wrong step can cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the cliffs of Cavach-Ijene a few years ago.
Miners in Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents for every kilogram of sulfur they extract
Once at the top, they make their way through the tourists, who photograph them as if they were monkeys from a circus, and, weary of carrying heavy baskets, they walk three kilometers to the scales that the mining company has placed just above them, at an altitude of 1,850 meters.
The company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, better still, its workers, is paid 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents) for every kilogram of sulfur.
Then it sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to petrochemical companies, since the mineral is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite, and even to bleach sugar.
"Because the norm is to carry 70 kilograms [70 lb], we earn about 46,000 rupees [US$3.8], or about $1.50 a day", explains Antô, who normally carries three items a day.
He spends three hours on each and is devastated at the end, but they allow him to save 138,000 rupees ($12) by the end of the day.
Although it seems a pittance for such an inhuman effort, it's three times what he would have earned in the field.
"The daily wage of the miners is very high by local standards, with a coffee harvest of 15,000 rupees ($1.40) a day and an average monthly wage of two million rupees ($1.60) ", explains a porter who used to work as a bricklayer on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (6.2 euros) a day, and the site was not so difficult, but Antō returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a reason that is as devastating as sulfur in Indonesia: "I married a girl from Bali, where there are only Hindus, and brought her to Java to convert to Islam".
Antônio has asthma, he can hardly breathe, he coughs constantly, and he has tears in his eyes from the toxic gases.
At the age of 27, Antônio spent three years risking his life in Kawah-Ijen, where sulfur had already started to affect him despite wearing a mask and glasses.
He has asthma, he can hardly breathe, he coughs constantly, and he has tears in his eyes from the toxic gases that the volcano is releasing.
It's the price he has to pay for achieving his dream.
"I'll work another two years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French", he promises in more than acceptable English.
Sentenced to life, this pleasant and intelligent young man could have been a tour guide, a waiter or a hotel porter, but instead he is doing the work of a mule.
Sharing a dirty wooden hut with other porters, he gets up every day at two o'clock in the morning because the sulfur does not stop flowing at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and shines in the darkness.
Defying the shadows, Antônio descends into the crater, illuminating his path with a small lantern attached to his helmet, which he bought with his own money.
About 400 porters carrying sulfur baskets on their shoulders from the bottom of the volcano
Despite its high profits, the mining company has not mechanised its sulfur extraction to save costs and does not provide any equipment to the carriers who work at their own expense and with such deprivations.
In fact, they do not even receive a portion of the 30,000 rupees ($1.50) photo fee, which, along with the 15,000 rupees ($1.2) entrance fee, the park's guards charge tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its mule people.
"This is a job for cattle, not people", says Badrusin, a 42-year-old hard-working porter who has spent three decades in Kawah Ijen since leaving college.
He can lift up to 400 pounds [110 kg], and he says he will work "as long as he can" because he needs money to pay for the education of his three children, ages 18 to 10.
I'm not retiring. I'm dying here because the volcano is my life.
Although the sulfur burns their throats and burns their eyes when the wind suddenly changes and traps the miners in the dense plumes of smoke coming out of the volcano, they are so hardy that no one complains of their severe illnesses... more serious, apparently, than their usual breathing problems, arthrosis, knee pain and shoulder ulcers that have deformed under the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unainik can now lift only 50 kilograms at the age of 53.
Each day, he and his companions haul 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks transport to a warehouse in Taman Sari, covering a distance of 11 miles [18 km] along a narrow path through the bush.
"I will not retire, I will die here, because the volcano is my whole life", says Unainik, opening his mouth wide, missing several teeth.
Of his five children, the eldest, 30 years old, also works as a sulfur transporter.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates from generation to generation one of the world's toughest jobs: what human mules do from Kawah-Ijen.
Singapore is looking for children to save the economy
Singaporeans blame career, stress, and housing and education costs for not having children.
"Singapore's population needs to grow".
I'm a patriot husband, you're my patriot wife, let's do our civic duty and create a life!
It may seem incredible that these lines are part of a mint bun commercial, but despite this - or perhaps because of it - this video became a hit on YouTube in Singapore earlier this year.
These phrases are part of a rap that uses local sayings like "Let's put bao in the oven" to mock the birth rate in Singapore.
The advertising agency that made this video, BBH, hopes to use advertising to bring attention to this problem in an entertaining way.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the power of music to get people to do "their national duty".
This thing is just for the Internet, so we needed to make it fun and funny.
It's the biggest problem in the country.
We're the worst in the world at reproducing our own kind, so we felt like this was the topic we needed to address.
We knew that the government was trying to do a lot of things, like launching pheromone perfumes or having flash-dating parties.
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but they didn't necessarily work.
So we thought, why not do the most creative thing we can do to solve this problem, and that's write a rap?
1.2 children
The one who doesn't take it so lightly is the Singaporean government.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
The state package for married couples and parents provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and provides tax breaks.
But all of this is inefficient.
Singapore is a wealthy and high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for its conservative leadership and strict public control.
The birth rate in Singapore, according to its National Population Office, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was below 2 -- what's known as the replacement percentage -- was 1976.
So why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Min, director of the Office of Marriage and Family Policy at the National Population Administration, says that "improved education" and "a wider range of career opportunities" are the reasons.
"It has allowed people to have a wider range of choices when it comes to life goals and priorities beyond marriage and family", she explains.
These changes in social norms have led to a rise in singleness and a delay in marriage and childbearing, which has led to a decline in Singapore's birth rate.
Meanwhile, immigration policies that aim to dramatically increase immigration to counter population decline are causing outrage among the local population.
There are websites in Singapore that have a hard-to-conceal xenophobia about many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are criticized for keeping their salaries low and not wanting to integrate.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons Singapore's ruling party scored its worst result in an election since independence last year.
After the election, there was an attempt to solve the problem, with quotas and higher taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While falling birth rates have some impact on the nation's economic growth, tax revenues, healthcare spending and immigration policies, Singapore's example is also beginning to have some unexpected consequences.
The government is making efforts to keep the number of small dwellings down.
For example, it's starting to affect the real estate sector.
The city development authority has moved to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes", that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These 46 square meter apartments are selling very well.
However, there is a view that they may promote a single-family lifestyle and discourage developers from building large family homes.
But Lim Yu Sun, CEO of homebuilding firm EL Developers, says their "shoe boxes" sell much faster than the more spacious ones.
They're more popular in the sense that they sell out for days, even weeks, faster than larger apartments.
As a result, our income is increasing.
However, he acknowledges that the new regulations provide clearer guidelines for developers who were previously barred from offering too many small apartments in the project.
Too much pressure .
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules may be a step towards increasing the national fertility rate, after talking to Singaporeans who work in the financial district of the center, it seems that they will not have much effect.
"People are very stressed, housing is expensive, and education is expensive, so many people put it off", says a young manager.
Other people can have children.
"But for me, it's important to manage my own money and time", says another 20-year-old.
Both men and women cite their careers, stress, and housing and education costs as reasons for not having children.
So as much as the government tries to encourage its citizens to have children, when it comes to having children, the final say is left to Singaporeans.
