UNASUR summit ends without the Lima Declaration
The 6th Summit of the President of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, announced earlier and theoretically signed by the seven mandatory participants.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI UNASUR regular meeting of heads of state and government, but sources in the Office and the Presidential Administration indicated on the homepage that it would be released after closing, but then confirmed that at some point it would be published on the Peruvian government website.
When asked about the text, they indicated that the content was set out by Peruvian President Ollanta Humala during brief press statements.
Journalists' access to information about the Summit was limited at all times.
During the day, only a video of the presidential assembly without sound was broadcast in the press room with the message "closed session, sound is prohibited".
The little information that circulated among reporters was conveyed by the press secretaries of some UNASUR governments present at the meeting, but not the Peruvian one.
The only document circulated during the day was a list of the participating presidents, which caused outrage among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who asked for more information.
The Peruvian presidential administration subsequently sent an email to the media with the summit's "final declaration", but it was a statement by Umala, not an official document that ended the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South American and Arab Nations (SASA) and, despite press pressure, the so-called Lima Declaration, which had been announced earlier, was not distributed.
The official website of the ASPA shows that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, Peruvian authorities tried to provide transmission systems for all journalists, but limited access to information as much as possible.
The summit also ended with Chile and Peru jointly deciding to accept the Hague court's verdict, which will settle a territorial dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, gathered at a regional meeting and ratified that they would abide by the ruling of the International Court of Justice, which begins hearing the case of both sides in The Hague on Monday, as part of the indictment that Lima brought against Santiago.
"We will respect and implement the decision that will clarify the differences that we are currently presenting to this international court", Umal said, alongside his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile was, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful settlement of disputes, pacts and international tribunals", added Piniera, and greeted Umalu with a handshake against the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they will comply with the International Court of Justice came just after Colombia protested this week against the Bogota Pact, under which it recognized its compliance with the court's rulings after a decision on the maritime boundaries with Nicaragua that it considered to be flawed.
The summit was held in the absence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chavez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR was suspended in 2011 after the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not attend the meeting.
The host president, Olyanta Umal, was responsible for opening the discussions in the morning and closing the summit, a little later in the afternoon, Lima time.
The Head of State read the final document, in which he said that 16 agreements were adopted and 31 projects were approved among South American countries, the amount of the proposed investments amounted to 17 billion dollars.
Among the agreements, he mentioned that UNASUR countries would take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding the residence agreements".
He said that action was being taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against civil uncertainty and organized transnational crime, actions to increase the availability of medicines, affordable Internet access in all parts of South America, and the collective and effective management of natural disaster risks".
As Europe is in crisis, "the economic union [of Latin America] should not have a triumphal basis, but should serve to expand our production base and foresee a better future for our cities", Umal added.
"We have decided to give priority to a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve connectivity in South America, especially in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and forming new economic patterns", the Peruvian president said in a message read.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five are related to Peru, and are limited to a transverse axis in its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two aimed at greater connectivity with Ecuador, but he did not provide more details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve its re-admission to the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, united and with good relations between neighbours was another theme emphasized at the summit.
In this regard, the President of Colombia, Juan Manuel Santos, said before starting the regional meeting that he hopes to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City to hold respectful negotiations on the maritime dispute resulting from the verdict of the international court challenged by Bogotá.
"The day after tomorrow (Saturday), I may meet with President Daniel Ortega", Santos said.
"We will review all these paths, they are not mutually exclusive, including the pact with Nicaragua will require discussion with Nicaragua", he stressed.
"With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him that we will handle this in the most civilized and respectful way possible", Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet Saturday in Mexico City, where they are scheduled to attend the inauguration of the new president of that country, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Also within the summit, the bloc's defense ministers met in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and unanimity on the issue of protecting the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay form UNASUR, although the latter has been suspended.
Peru has a temporary presidency in the regional bloc.
