AIDS deaths today are the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 when he was told that his test for AIDS had come back positive.
"I felt deaf", he recalls, "despite the doctor's tact, I was very upset.
The young man hid it from his family.
Deciding to cope with his illness on his own, he wanted to learn as much as possible about it, and his efforts paid off - he had just celebrated his 43rd birthday.
Fabrizio is one of the "oldest" HIV patients at the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he arrived in 1994 after overcoming many obstacles.
He's been living with HIV for 22 years, which was hard to believe in the early 1990s, when there were so few treatment options, so little knowledge of the disease, so much bias.
Even the director of the clinic at the Mexican Institute of Social Welfare refused to say goodbye to him "because he had a cut".
In other words, in those days, having AIDS was a sentence.
Now it's possible to survive with this syndrome and do so without compromising quality of life.
Yet, many people still come to the hospital unaware of their illness when the virus has already damaged their immune system and they suffer from opportunistic infections.
Thirty-one years after the world's first AIDS cases were reported, "the big breakthrough so far is that the survival of the patient who starts treatment on time is exactly the same as the survival of the general population", said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HCG HIV Unit, citing a report in April this year in a prestigious scientific journal.
Andrade Villanueva, an infectious disease expert and HIV/AIDS expert, explained that since 2008, scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a verdict, but that the length and quality of life depend on the extent of damage to the immune system that patients have at the time of diagnosis, with the best life expectancy for non-drug users being up to 30 years with 200 CD4s and up to 50 years with 500 CD4s.
Simply put, this means that a person diagnosed as HIV-positive at age 25 "can live safely to 75 years of age if he is kept under control", he explained.
To gauge this progress, it is worth remembering that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although deaths have declined significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS fell from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNAIDS annual report), and it is also true that since the onset of AIDS, 60 percent of the patients in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths have been reported as of May this year; however, it is claimed that there has been widespread access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
- Why are there still fatalities?
- I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's how things are at our hospital.
For at least the last 12 years, we have not had a shortage of medicines, the problem is that patients come very late because they don't know they're infected, which is late in the disease.
He cited the devastating data: "Nine out of ten patients come when they already have some sort of opportunistic infection; what needs to be done to have a greater impact on overall mortality is to diagnose at an earlier stage, and therefore to provide mass detection samples to all people who ask for it".
The proposal is echoed by experts and officials of the State Council for AIDS Prevention in Jalisco (COESIDA) as well as patients like Fabrizio, who went to a private lab for testing simply because a friend had done it and despite his young age, he was already in the AIDS stage and even had Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancer tumor that is a common complication.
It's different when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're going to die and they don't want to know.
"I'd rather die than get drunk three times a week", they say.
I'm making some positive changes, eating right, exercising, taking my medication.
To this day, his parents only know that he had cancer.
I live a normal life like anyone else.
"I work, I have many classes, I travel, I have an active sex life, but with mutual responsibility, I take care of myself and the other person", said Fabrizio, who agreed to share his personal life with MILENIO JALISCO to promote his statement to those who are now in fear in the context of World AIDS Day.
Let them be tested for the risk of infection, let them know as soon as possible if they are HIV positive, the better, and if they already have a diagnosis, let them know that they can live like any other person, with responsibility.
This is his message summarizing the theme of the fight against AIDS this year 2012.
Condoms are on the counter .
There are huge gaps between health programs and the average citizen, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist in Guadalajara who has covered HIV.
And the biggest thing is prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, "the condoms have actually increased in distribution, we used to be given one or two, now we are given a hundred packs, which is very good, but it turns out there are people who still don't have access to condoms", he said.
Teenagers are among the most vulnerable to new infections.
"Why do you need them?" is a popular question, with scorn and condemnation from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy workers and health workers, which teenagers do not want to hear, the propagandist said.
I propose to change this inefficient distribution; to have condoms not just on the shelves, but in the vending machines in public toilets in places where young people frequent.
It's not encouraging debauchery.
It's not about paying for beer and a motel, Governor Emilio Gonzalez said when asked if condoms are available under his administration.
"It's not sexuality, it's making condoms available to people who are already sexually active", he said.
Key facts about Jalisco
A total of 13,435 cases were recorded (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
