Larry Hagman, whose role as oil tycoon J.R. Ewing in the 1980s television series Dallas became a symbol of greed, has died.
He was 81.
Hagman, who returned this year as J.R. in the new season of Dallas, died Friday night from complications from cancer, according to a family statement provided to The Associated Press by Warner Bros., Dallas' production studio.
"Larry has returned to his beloved hometown of Dallas, once again playing the iconic role he loved most", his family said.
Larry's family and closest friends were with him in Dallas for the Thanksgiving Day Fair.
Linda Gray, who played Hagman's wife in the original series and the sequel, was with Hagman when he died in a Dallas hospital, her spokesman Jeffrey Lane said.
He brought joy to all who knew him.
He was creative, generous, funny, kind and talented, and I'm gonna miss him so much.
"He was an original personality and lived a full life", Gray confirmed in a statement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992 and admitted to drinking for many years.
In 1995, he was diagnosed with a malignant tumor in his liver and underwent a liver transplant.
Long before Dallas, Hagman gained fame on television for his role as a decent type in the light comedy I Dream of Jeannie, which aired on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
He played Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive genie girl, played by Barbara Eden, and begins living with her under the same roof.
He was also the lead character in two comedies that rarely aired, "The Good Life" (NBC, 1971-72) and "Here We Go Again" (ABC, 1973).
His film work included critically acclaimed roles in The Group, Harry and Tonto and Primary Colors.
But it was his masterful interpretation of the delightfully disgusting J.R. that brought Hagman to the pinnacle of fame.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other characters in its entourage aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The slogan "Who shot J.R.?", designed to create a buzz around the emotional episode in which Hagman's character is nearly killed, sparked international discussion and millions of dollars being risked at bookmakers.
It also helped to attract a record-breaking audience at the time.
When the answer was given in the November 1980 episode, an average of 41 million television viewers watched it, making Dallas the second most watched entertainment program in history, after the final of "MASH" in 1983 with 50 million viewers.
It was J.R.'s sister-in-law, Christine (played by Mary Crosby), who shot him.
J.R. stopped her and then threatened to charge her with prostitution if she didn't leave town, but others had reasons to attack him, too.
Hagman played Ewing as a voracious corrupt with a charismatic smile: a dishonest businessman and unfaithful husband who wanted his alcoholic wife, Sue Ellen (Linda Gray), to be put into treatment.
"I know what should be on J.R.'s tombstone", Hagman said in 1988.
It should say, "Here lies the good citizen J.R. Ewing".
It's the only deal he's ever lost.
Victoria Principal, also the heroine of the original series, recalled Hagman on Friday as someone "huge, both on and off screen".
He is unforgettable and irreplaceable to millions of fans around the world, and in the hearts of every one of us who was lucky enough to know and love him.
